      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "d7f8c1091c174d82",
        "text": "The separation between programmers and users is unlikely to completely evaporate, as there will always be a need for technical expertise to develop and maintain software applications. However, as technology continues to advance, it is possible that the degree of separation may become less pronounced, with more user-friendly and intuitive interfaces that require less technical knowledge to operate.\n\nWhether or not users want this separation to evaporate may depend on a variety of factors, such as their individual level of technical expertise and their willingness to learn new skills. Some users may prefer a more hands-on approach to using software, while others may prefer a more streamlined and intuitive experience.\n\nThe industry's perspective on this issue may also depend on a variety of factors, such as the nature of the products and services being offered, the target audience for those products and services, and the competitive landscape in which the industry operates. While some companies may seek to maintain a degree of control over their users through technical expertise, others may seek to empower their users through more user-friendly interfaces and tools.\n\nThe fact that the browser remains a central platform for software development and delivery does pose some challenges in terms of addressing the separation between programmers and users. However, as new technologies continue to emerge, it is possible that we may see new platforms and tools that are better equipped to bridge this gap and provide a more seamless experience for both programmers and end-users."
